The information on this page covers the most common types of travel and reflects the UK government’s understanding of the rules currently in place. Unless otherwise stated, this information is for travellers using a full ‘British Citizen’ passport.
The authorities in the country or territory you’re travelling to are responsible for setting and enforcing the rules for entry. If you’re unclear about any aspect of the entry requirements, or you need further reassurance, you’ll need to contact the embassy, high commission or consulate of the country or territory you’re travelling to.
You should also consider checking with your transport provider or travel company to make sure your passport and other travel documents meet their requirements.
Restrictions in response to coronavirus
Airports in Slovenia re-opened for passenger flights on 11 May. You should consult airlines for details of flight options, to and from Slovenia.
Passenger train connections between Slovenia and Austria remain suspended.
The Slovene authorities have announced new border entry procedures.
Health checks are conducted at all border entry points. British visitors who display signs of coronavirus infections will be refused entry, unless they hold a permanent residence permit for Slovenia.
UK nationals entering Slovenia will be required to undertake a 14-day quarantine on arrival unless they meet one of the following exemptions, which do not require quarantine on entry: * UK nationals holding permanent or temporary residence permits in Slovenia;
* A UK National, EU citizen or citizen from a Schengen country travelling through Slovenia to another country on the same day. * A person who has a confirmed reservation of an overnight stay in a tourist establishment in Slovenia and proves this with proof of reservation. * a person who is a close relative of a citizen of the Republic of Slovenia or lives with him in a common household and has permanent or temporary residence in a country of the European Union or another country of the Schengen area; * A person who has proof of a planned medical examination or intervention in Slovenia on the day of crossing the border. * A person who attends the funeral of a close relative in an EU country or another Schengen country and leaves or returns to Slovenia on the same day and has proof of the date and time of the funeral. * A person who owns real estate or a registered aircraft or watercraft in Slovenia and possess proof of such ownership, together with close family members. * Cross-border :daily or weekly working migrants with an employment relationship in one of the Member States of the EU or another Schengen country with proof for the reason for crossing the border as a daily or weekly migrant; * A person in commercial traffic or activities who can provide evidence of performing these activiites in Slovenia or abroad and returns across the border on the same day or who submits a negative test result for Covid 19 that is not older than three days. In the case of a person employed by a foreign company providing a service in Slovenia and residing in Slovenia, this person must also submit the address of their residence in Slovenia and a negative Covid 19 test result not older than three days.
* A person seconded to or from a mission in the international transport sector and who demonstrates this at the time of crossing the border. * A person who carries out the transit of goods to Slovenia or from Slovenia and for freight transport in transit.
* A person travelling with a diplomatic passport. * A person who provides services for the provision of public services (e.g.,, energy, health, transport, utilities) for which a certificate has been issued by the competent ministry and failure to provide these services due to quarantine could cause major social or economic damage.
* A member of the protection and rescue services, health care, police, firefighters and persons carrying out humanitarian transport for Slovenia, who cross the border in the performance of these tasks. * A citizen of Slovenia, Croatia, Austria, Italy or Hungary who is a dual owner or tenant of land and has their own land on both sides of the border and performs agricultural work.
* A person who crosses the border due to involvement in education or scientific research in Slovenia, the EU or other Schengen countries and provides proof of this with appropriate evidence and returns on the same day. * A person who crosses the border daily or occasionally because they are employed in an educational institution, visits Slovenia or abroad as a higher education teacher or is involved in a research project in Slovenia or abroad and proves this with appropriate evidence.
* A person who crosses the border for family reasons in order to maintain contact with close family members and returns across the border on the same day.
All arriving travellers will be given advice at the border, regarding the steps they may need to take.
If you enter Slovenia you are advised to carry with you evidence of your reason for travel (for example, onward travel bookings; proof of residency; a work permit).
Neighbouring countries have reduced restrictions on entry from Slovenia. See travel advice for Austria, Croatia, Hungary and Italy.
For information on how to return to the UK from Slovenia, see Return to the UK
If you remain in Slovenia, you should be aware that for stays longer than 90 days, you will be required to register as a Temporary Resident. This requires you to submit a form requesting temporary residency, which should be sent to the Slovene authorities via registered post as proof of your application.
Please contact the Uprava Enota (the department that handles these applications) at +386 1 306 3035 or at ue.ljubljana@gov.si. The department is open Monday to Thursday from 0800-1800, and on Friday from 0800-1400.
Passport validity
Your passport should be valid for the proposed duration of your stay; you do not need any additional period of validity on your passport beyond this.
The rules on travel will stay the same until 31 December 2020.
Visas  
If you hold a British Citizen passport, you don’t need a visa to enter Slovenia. If you’re planning a stay of longer than 3 months, see our Living in Slovenia guide and contact the Slovene Embassy if you have further questions.
The rules on travel will stay the same until 31 December 2020.
UK Emergency Travel Documents
UK Emergency Travel Documents (ETDs) are accepted for entry, airside transit and exit from Slovenia.
